    body: "Proportionalism is a moral theory, advanced by some twentieth-century Catholic theologians, which holds that the moral quality of an act cannot be determined by its object alone but must also weigh the proportion of good and bad effects. Under this view, no act is intrinsically evil — any act could be justified if the proportion of premoral goods to premoral evils is favorable. Pope John Paul II definitively rejected proportionalism in Veritatis Splendor (1993), affirming that certain acts are intrinsically evil by their very object and can never be justified regardless of intentions or consequences.",
