    oneLiner: "The moral system holding that when there is a solidly probable opinion favoring liberty, one may follow it even if the opinion favoring the law is more probable.",
    body: "Probabilism, developed by Dominican Bartolomé de Medina (1577) and later championed by the Jesuits, addresses cases of genuine moral doubt. It holds that a truly probable opinion (one supported by serious arguments or reputable theologians) may be followed in good conscience even when the opposing view is somewhat more probable. This system resists both laxism (any flimsy excuse suffices) and rigorism (one must always follow the safest course). St. Alphonsus Liguori refined it into equiprobabilism, which became the standard Catholic approach.",
