    body: "Tutiorism (from tutior, 'safer') demands that whenever there is doubt about whether an action is permissible, one must choose the option that avoids any risk of sin. While seemingly pious, the Church ultimately rejected strict tutiorism as excessively burdensome. Pope Alexander VIII condemned the proposition that it is always necessary to follow the more probable opinion (a form of tutiorism) in 1690. Moderate tutiorism, however, still applies in certain cases where grave harm is at stake, such as the validity of sacraments.",
