    oneLiner: "The rejected theory that mortal sin requires a total existential rejection of God, such that individual grave acts cannot by themselves sever the relationship with God.",
    body: "Fundamental option theory, influenced by Rahner and other transcendental Thomists, proposed that mortal sin is not a single bad act but a deep-seated, fundamental orientation of the whole person against God. While acknowledging a kernel of truth (the moral life does involve deep dispositions), Veritatis Splendor (1993) rejected the theory insofar as it denies that specific concrete acts — such as adultery, murder, or apostasy — can of themselves constitute mortal sin and sever one's relationship with God. The Church insists that a single gravely disordered act, done with full knowledge and deliberate consent, is sufficient for mortal sin.",
